      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. i was also reading something about the loss landscape and how it affects gradient descent. if i don't normalize, does it actually change the shape of the optimization path? like, does it make it harder for the algorithm to find the minimum?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, failing to normalize significantly changes the shape of the optimization path in the loss landscape, often creating an elongated \"valley\" rather than a smooth, round bowl. This elongation causes gradient descent to take inefficient, zig-zag steps instead of a straight line directly toward the minimum, drastically slowing down convergence. Essentially, the algorithm struggles to navigate extreme inclines and declines simultaneously, which can lead to unstable updates or getting stuck in local minima near suboptimal solutions.",
      "source": "target",
